136
00:06:12,082 --> 00:06:14,984
Then there is protanopia.

137
00:06:14,984 --> 00:06:17,787
This is another kind of red-green colorblindness.

138
00:06:17,787 --> 00:06:18,367
So we have the two.

139
00:06:18,367 --> 00:06:21,230
But it's far less common.

140
00:06:21,230 --> 00:06:25,473
So this is around a quarter of colorblind men, roughly.

141
00:06:25,473 --> 00:06:28,236
So this is all about red light, reduced sensitivity.

142
00:06:29,088 --> 00:06:32,430
And so these people confuse black with red.

143
00:06:32,430 --> 00:06:35,333
So the intensity of red is greatly diminished.

144
00:06:35,333 --> 00:06:37,034
And the difference here can be,

145
00:06:37,034 --> 00:06:40,036
it's like the difference between a light being on or off.

146
00:06:40,036 --> 00:06:43,299
And so black, like for the purposes of color blindness,

147
00:06:43,299 --> 00:06:44,580
we have to consider black a color.

148
00:06:44,580 --> 00:06:48,963
Browns, greens, reds, and oranges often get blurred as well.

149
00:06:48,963 --> 00:06:51,785
Quite a lot of crossover with deuteranopia.

150
00:06:51,785 --> 00:06:53,026
Blues, purples, and dark pinks.

151
00:06:53,026 --> 00:06:56,308
And many reds and oranges, of course, very dim.

152
00:06:57,823 --> 00:07:01,525
And the third one, much rarer, is tritanopia.

153
00:07:01,525 --> 00:07:04,786
So this is very rare indeed.

154
00:07:04,786 --> 00:07:07,088
This is only around one in 10,000 people,

155
00:07:07,088 --> 00:07:11,830
although I have met one tritanope on this trip so far.

156
00:07:11,830 --> 00:07:13,671
