00:11:59,859 --> 00:12:02,501
I'm pressing the wrong damn button.

264
00:12:02,501 --> 00:12:05,583
Because even though I,

265
00:12:05,583 --> 00:12:07,564
like even though there are two other parts

266
00:12:07,564 --> 00:12:09,326
of the language there,

267
00:12:09,326 --> 00:12:12,107
like the affirmative button is on the left as usual.

268
00:12:12,107 --> 00:12:15,910
And it looks like the receiver is picking it up.

269
00:12:15,910 --> 00:12:17,491
And in the stress of the moment,

270
00:12:17,491 --> 00:12:19,252
even I, knowing I'm colorblind,

271
00:12:19,252 --> 00:12:20,073
I still go for the color.

272
00:12:20,682 --> 00:12:22,802
And I went for the button I thought was green,

273
00:12:22,802 --> 00:12:24,582
which was the wrong one.

274
00:12:24,582 --> 00:12:26,423
So I was hanging up loads and loads of calls

275
00:12:26,423 --> 00:12:27,743
and I didn't know why.

276
00:12:27,743 --> 00:12:31,684
Fashion is a bit of a write-off.

277
00:12:31,684 --> 00:12:33,924
I quite like that while I like,

278
00:12:33,924 --> 00:12:35,805
one step is that there are labels in clothing

279
00:12:35,805 --> 00:12:37,245
to say which colors they are.

280
00:12:37,245 --> 00:12:39,465
That doesn't mean I know which colors go with what.

281
00:12:39,465 --> 00:12:43,846
So I, and if I do want to try and dress fashionably,

282
00:12:43,846 --> 00:12:47,007
I genuinely need help.

283
00:12:47,007 --> 00:12:48,287
But, or I just wear gray all the time.

284
00:12:49,599 --> 00:12:51,920
Apparently that's something called, is that burgundy?

285
00:12:51,920 --> 00:12:54,880
A mythical creature called burgundy.

286
00:12:54,880 --> 00:12:56,821
I'll take your word for it.

287
00:12:56,821 --> 00:13:00,902
And same goes for, like, there are lots of people

288
00:13:00,902 --> 00:13:03,522
around GDC with different colored hair,

289
00:13:03,522 --> 00:13:05,883
and I have no idea what it is.

290
00:13:05,883 --> 00:13:08,663
Like, and I see a lot of what may or may not be

291
00:13:08,663 --> 00:13:11,424
blue, purple, or turquoise hair, or pink.

292
00:13:11,424 --> 00:13:14,464
Like, I, and it's like Schrodinger's hair color.

293
00:13:14,464 --> 00:13:16,005
It's one of those, I don't know which one.

294
00:13:17,250 --> 00:13:21,633
And if this is embarrassing to anyone, I don't know that either.

295
00:13:21,633 --> 00:13:27,676
Only a few years ago I realized that blushing is real.

296
00:13:27,676 --> 00:13:29,938
I thought it was a cartoon thing.

297
00:13:29,938 --> 00:13:33,220
And it was only a few years ago I realized, wait, it's real,

298
00:13:33,220 --> 00:13:35,722
but the colorblindness stops me from seeing it.

299
00:13:35,722 --> 00:13:39,404
And it's really annoying, this social cue that for all this time

300
00:13:39,404 --> 00:13:41,845
I could have been using and understanding people.

301
00:13:44,615 --> 00:13:46,715
This one came up last year, actually.

302
00:13:46,715 --> 00:13:49,736
This one affected a lot of people.

303
00:13:49,736 --> 00:13:54,137
So the uniforms in the, this is of course soccer,

304
00:13:54,137 --> 00:13:56,118
like I'm used to calling it football.

305
00:13:56,118 --> 00:13:58,598
Everything was going wrong here.

306
00:13:58,598 --> 00:14:01,379
So the two players were being indistinguishable

307
00:14:01,379 --> 00:14:03,299
from each other with the colorblindness.

308
00:14:03,299 --> 00:14:06,380
And also some of the players, they looked like the pitch.

309
00:14:06,380 --> 00:14:08,881
Like they blend into the green of the grass.

310
00:14:09,576 --> 00:14:12,077
So it's not just distinguishing element A from element B,

311
00:14:12,077 --> 00:14:14,918
but it's both elements from the environment.

312
00:14:14,918 --> 00:14:17,180
This is actually very translatable to games.

313
00:14:17,180 --> 00:14:20,381
There's something else that I've never seen.

314
00:14:20,381 --> 00:14:22,962
I've never seen that.

315
00:14:22,962 --> 00:14:25,143
That's not what I'd identify as.

316
00:14:25,143 --> 00:14:29,445
Like, in my eyes, that's not what my skin color looks like.

317
00:14:29,445 --> 00:14:31,986
I look like this.

318
00:14:31,986 --> 00:14:33,087
And so do all of you, by the way.

319
00:14:33,772 --> 00:14:37,994
Like, I know other people have looked at the simulators I see

320
00:14:37,994 --> 00:14:40,555
and like to see my colorblindness, and they're like,

321
00:14:40,555 --> 00:14:41,376
oh, everybody's green.

322
00:14:41,376 --> 00:14:43,497
And I was like, okay, yeah.

323
00:14:43,497 --> 00:14:44,337
When I was in primary school,

324
00:14:44,337 --> 00:14:46,158
I thought my friends had green skin.

325
00:14:46,158 --> 00:14:48,840
Because normally you don't have to tell children

326
00:14:48,840 --> 00:14:50,781
nobody's green.

327
00:14:50,781 --> 00:14:53,262
I was just going by what I could see.

328
00:14:53,262 --> 00:14:59,005
And to accommodate for the other types of colorblindness,

329
00:14:59,005 --> 00:14:59,625
this is how they identify.

330
00:14:59,625 --> 00:15:02,247
So this is how protonopes see themselves,

331
00:15:02,247 --> 00:15:03,287
how tritonopes see themselves.

332
00:15:04,045 --> 00:15:08,867
Medical emergencies are often missing a lot of information.

333
00:15:08,867 --> 00:15:10,988
I've had someone fainting in front of me before,

334
00:15:10,988 --> 00:15:12,588
and his skin white as a sheet,

335
00:15:12,588 --> 00:15:13,989
and I had no idea there was anything wrong with him.

336
00:15:13,989 --> 00:15:18,170
Until one of the ladies from Brown came in,

337
00:15:18,170 --> 00:15:21,811
I was like, oh my God, I'm getting the nurse.

338
00:15:21,811 --> 00:15:23,051
But he was fine. He was fine in the end.

339
00:15:23,982 --> 00:15:29,206
So, a lot of people have some ideas and assumptions about colorblindness and what it can and cannot

340
00:15:29,206 --> 00:15:30,106
let you do.

341
00:15:30,106 --> 00:15:31,968
So, the question, can you drive?

342
00:15:31,968 --> 00:15:35,890
And the answer is, so can you distinguish traffic lights?

343
00:15:35,890 --> 00:15:37,832
And the answer is generally yes.

344
00:15:37,832 --> 00:15:41,254
The traffic light systems are generally pretty well thought out.

345
00:15:41,254 --> 00:15:46,278
At night, red and yellow lights, or red and amber lights will often look the same, but

346
00:15:46,278 --> 00:15:49,640
because of the pattern and the timing of them, it doesn't matter.

347
00:15:50,303 --> 00:15:53,986
So, for me, if I can see the green light, that means go.

348
00:15:53,986 --> 00:15:56,869
If I can see the flashing yellow light, at least in the UK,

349
00:15:56,869 --> 00:15:57,429
that means go.

350
00:15:57,429 --> 00:15:59,831
Everything else means stop.

351
00:15:59,831 --> 00:16:01,453
And so it's absolutely fine.

352
00:16:01,453 --> 00:16:04,315
So, we're good.

353
00:16:04,315 --> 00:16:05,977
Now, this one, a lot of people bring up,

354
00:16:05,977 --> 00:16:08,879
and this was popularized by the film Little Miss Sunshine.

355
00:16:08,879 --> 00:16:11,742
One of the characters, colorblind, wanted to be a pilot.

356
00:16:11,742 --> 00:16:14,324
And was told, you can't be a pilot if you're colorblind.

357
00:16:14,324 --> 00:16:15,425
But is that true?

358
00:16:15,425 --> 00:16:16,846
And the answer is, it's maybe.

359
00:16:18,635 --> 00:16:22,376
It's like, it depends on the strength of your colorblindness

360
00:16:22,376 --> 00:16:24,657
and how intense it is.

361
00:16:24,657 --> 00:16:25,737
So you would be, you can expect to be tested

362
00:16:25,737 --> 00:16:30,098
as an individual against the symbols and stuff they have.

363
00:16:30,098 --> 00:16:32,338
So if you can practically handle their stuff,

364
00:16:32,338 --> 00:16:35,259
even colorblind people can fly planes.

365
00:16:35,259 --> 00:16:37,159
Now this is my favorite slide.

366
00:16:37,159 --> 00:16:41,220
Does everyone recognize this?

367
00:16:41,220 --> 00:16:42,841
Yeah, okay, we're doing this.

368
00:16:42,841 --> 00:16:46,722
Okay, raise your hands if you see a black and blue dress.

369
00:16:48,548 --> 00:16:49,328
I'll have a look around.

370
00:16:49,328 --> 00:16:51,449
Okay, hands down.

371
00:16:51,449 --> 00:16:54,011
And those that see white and gold.

372
00:16:54,011 --> 00:16:57,633
That is about 50-50, that's amazing.

373
00:16:57,633 --> 00:17:00,074
I love it.

374
00:17:00,074 --> 00:17:01,935
I see that, it's not that different.

375
00:17:01,935 --> 00:17:08,038
But when this happened, this was the best week of my life.

376
00:17:08,038 --> 00:17:11,320
Because it was like the world went colorblind

377
00:17:11,320 --> 00:17:13,701
for about a week and had no idea how to handle it.

378
00:17:14,497 --> 00:17:18,458
Because I don't remember not knowing I was colorblind.

379
00:17:18,458 --> 00:17:21,539
I found out very early in life.

380
00:17:21,539 --> 00:17:25,520
The question, why have you drawn the sea purple, Doug?

381
00:17:25,520 --> 00:17:27,860
I haven't, it's blue.

382
00:17:27,860 --> 00:17:30,021
It leads to a diagnosis fairly quickly.

383
00:17:30,021 --> 00:17:33,622
But what this also means is,

384
00:17:33,622 --> 00:17:38,003
knowing that I've been colorblind the whole time

385
00:17:38,003 --> 00:17:39,804
is knowledge that what I'm seeing might not be real,

386
00:17:39,804 --> 00:17:40,324
might not be right.

387
00:17:40,940 --> 00:17:42,100
And I'm used to that.

388
00:17:42,100 --> 00:17:43,181
I'm used to being told,

389
00:17:43,181 --> 00:17:45,422
actually, no, that's not what this is,

390
00:17:45,422 --> 00:17:47,683
this thing that's right in front of your eyes.

391
00:17:47,683 --> 00:17:51,025
But people with normal vision, normal color vision,

392
00:17:51,025 --> 00:17:52,706
they're not used to that.

393
00:17:52,706 --> 00:17:55,067
I had a really curious experience.

394
00:17:55,067 --> 00:17:57,368
I was helping out at some medical students' exams

395
00:17:57,368 --> 00:17:57,989
as a dummy patient,

396
00:17:57,989 --> 00:18:00,910
and one of the things they had to do

397
00:18:00,910 --> 00:18:02,111
was giving a colorblind test.

398
00:18:02,111 --> 00:18:03,692
So they said, oh, get Doug in.

399
00:18:03,692 --> 00:18:04,532
He's actually colorblind.

400
00:18:05,246 --> 00:18:08,428
And so the student comes, they have around seven minutes

401
00:18:08,428 --> 00:18:10,389
to run the Ishihara plate test,

402
00:18:10,389 --> 00:18:12,750
which is the dots and the circles that you see quite often.

403
00:18:12,750 --> 00:18:17,553
And then they have about seven minutes to do that

404
00:18:17,553 --> 00:18:19,254
and then they'll move on to something else.

405
00:18:19,254 --> 00:18:21,375
One of the students finished quite quickly.

406
00:18:21,375 --> 00:18:23,796
So went through the diagnosis, it was fine.

407
00:18:23,796 --> 00:18:25,517
And I was sat there with him and the examiner.

408
00:18:26,228 --> 00:18:27,790
And I had time, I asked,

409
00:18:27,790 --> 00:18:30,713
do you guys see anything in this plate?

410
00:18:30,713 --> 00:18:33,716
So it was one of the plates that I knew where,

411
00:18:33,716 --> 00:18:35,838
because of my color blindness, I could see the number.

412
00:18:35,838 --> 00:18:36,639
It was very cleverly made.

413
00:18:36,639 --> 00:18:39,082
But the language was interesting in the response.

414
00:18:39,082 --> 00:18:42,145
They didn't say, I can't see a number.

415
00:18:42,145 --> 00:18:43,947
They said, there is no number there.

416
00:18:43,947 --> 00:18:45,889
And I said, well, I can see a number.

417
00:18:45,889 --> 00:18:47,691
And they said, no, there is no number there.

418
00:18:48,963 --> 00:18:50,724
and they're not used to this.

419
00:18:50,724 --> 00:18:52,946
Like, they're not used to the idea that,

420
00:18:52,946 --> 00:18:54,167
and they're used to, like, if they can see it,

421
00:18:54,167 --> 00:18:56,889
it's there, and that's all there is.

422
00:18:56,889 --> 00:18:57,830
It was really interesting.

423
00:18:57,830 --> 00:18:59,592
It's like a little philosophical, you know,

424
00:18:59,592 --> 00:19:00,292
step up for me, so.

